\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. A. littoralis} (Gouan) Parl.,{\i  Fl. Ital. }{\b 1}: 461 (1850) (incl. {\i A. intermedius} Regel, {\i A. pungens} (Bieb.) C. Koch). Rhizomes and stolons extensively creeping; flowering stems up to 25 cm, erect or decumbent. Leaves and sheaths strongly and closely ridged, glabrous to sparsely hairy on abaxial surface; leaves up to 5 cm but often much less, glabrous to sparsely hairy on adaxial surface. Inflorescence 10-50 × 4-10 mm, narrowly ovoid; axis of inflorescence and spikes minutely aculeolate to shortly pubescent; lower spikes on same side of axis not overlapping, at least on main inflorescences. Lower glume 1-2·5 mm, 1- to 4-veined; upper glume 1·5-3 mm, 3- to 6-veined. Lemma 1·5-4 mm including mucro, 9- to 11-veined; mucro 0·1-0·3 mm. Glumes and lemma glabrous or hairy on hyaline margins, aculeolate on main veins. 2n = 20. {\i Sandy places, mostly maritime and saline. Mediterranean region and S.E. Europe.} Al Bl Bu Co Cr Ga Gr Hs It Ju Rm Rs (W, K, E) Si Tu.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Typical{\i  A. littoralis} has glabrous or very sparsely hairy leaves and sheaths, and glabrous lemmas 2-3·5 mm.{\b  A. intermedius} Regel,{\i  Bull. Soc. Nat. Moscou }{\b 41}({\b 2}): 292 (1869) ({\i A. littoralis} subsp.{\i  intermedius} (Regel) Tzvelev), from S.E. Russia, differs only in its more densely hairy leaves and somewhat longer lemmas (2·3-4 mm), and{\b  A. pungens} (Bieb.) C. Koch,{\i  Linnaea}{\b  21}: 408 (1848) ({\i A. littoralis} subsp.{\i  pungens }(Bieb.) Tzvelev), also from S.E. Russia, differs only in its somewhat shorter lemmas (1·5-3 mm) which are hairy on the hyaline margins. Each probably merits only varietal status.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. A. lagopoides} (L.) Trin. ex Thwaites{\i  Enum. Pl. Zeyl.} 374 (1864) ({\i A. repens} (Desf.) Parl.). Like {\b 1} but more compact; stolons and rhizomes far-creeping or not; flowering stems up to 15 cm; at least the lower leaves and sheaths hairy on abaxial surface; leaves mostly less than 15 mm; inflorescence 5-20 × 4-8 mm, ovoid to suborbicular; adjacent spikes on same side of axis closely imbricate; glumes and lemmas hairy on dorsal surface.{\i  Maritime sands. Islands of the Mediterranean region eastwards from Sicilia.} Cr Si ?Tu. ({\i N. & N.E. Africa, S. & S.C. Asia}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   {\b 1} and {\b 2} are usually quite distinct, but intermediates sometimes occur, especially in W. Asia. Specimens with hairy leaves and sparsely hairy lemmas, but otherwise resembling {\i A. littoralis}, have been referred to {\i A. littoralis} var.{\i  intermedius} Cosson & Durieu or var. {\i hispidulus} Halácsy.
